o controversies including the abatement of water pollution, apportionment of river waters, economic development, flood control, inland fisheries, marine fisheries, and restoration to rivers of anadromous fish, such as salmon and shad. The process for entering into interstate and federal-interstate compacts is explained in detail, as is the exercise of original jurisdiction by the US Supreme Court to resolve intractable interstate controversies involving interpretation of provisions of compacts, water apportionment, and water pollution abatement. Zimmerman concludes by calling for the President, Congress, governors, state legislatures, and local governments to devote more attention and resources to finding solutions for water-related problems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInterstate agreements -- United States. 0aInterstate agreementszUnited States. 0aWater -- Government policy -- United States. 0aWater -- Law and legislation -- United States. 0aWater resources development -- Law and legislation -- United States. 0aWater resources developmentxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aWaterxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aWaterxLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aWater-supply -- Management. 0aWater-supplyxManagement. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPolitics and Law : State and Local Politics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438444499423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438444499/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles